The `loop` keyword tells Rust to execute a block of code over and over again forever, or until you explicitly tell it to stop.

```rust
loop {
    println!("again!");
}
```
*(If you run this, you'll need to press Ctrl-C to force pause your terminal!)*

To stop an infinite loop, you place the `break` keyword somewhere inside the block.

```rust
let mut i = 0;
loop {
    i += 1;
    if i == 5 {
        break; // Stops the loop entirely!
    }
}
```

Just like `let if`, you can use `loop` to evaluate and return a value when it finishes! You just pass the value directly after the `break` keyword.

```rust
let mut counter = 0;
let result = loop {
    counter += 1;
    if counter == 10 {
        break counter * 2;
    }
};
// result is 20!
```
